        <div class="scenario">
            <div class="scenario-title"><span class="emoji">üè†</span> Your Current Situation</div>
            <div class="scenario-content">
                <p><strong>What you're doing now:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin-left: 20px; line-height: 2; font-size: 1.05em;">
                    <li>Renting out a <strong>residential property</strong> to a company (for the director to live in)</li>
                    <li>Planning to rent out a <strong>commercial property</strong> as well</li>
                    <li>Currently <strong>NOT registered for GST</strong></li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 15px; font-size: 1.05em;"><strong>Why? Because your total income is below ‚Çπ20 Lakhs per year.</strong></p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="highlight">
            <p style="margin: 0;"><strong>üìä Example Scenario:</strong></p>
            <p style="margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 0;">Residential rent: ‚Çπ12 Lakhs/year | Commercial rent: ‚Çπ9 Lakhs/year | <strong>Total: ‚Çπ21 Lakhs</strong> ‚ö†Ô∏è EXCEEDS ‚Çπ20 LAKHS - GST registration mandatory!</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="grid">
            <div class="card">
                <h2><span class="emoji">üí∞</span> The Key Number: ‚Çπ20 Lakhs</h2>
                <p>When your <strong>combined rental income</strong> from both properties reaches <strong>‚Çπ20 Lakhs per year</strong>, a big change happens...</p>
                <div class="amount-box">
                    ‚Çπ20,00,000
                    <p style="font-size: 0.8em; margin-top: 5px; font-weight: normal;">This is the GST Registration Threshold</p>
                </div>
                <p><strong>Example:</strong> If you earn ‚Çπ12 Lakhs from residential + ‚Çπ10 Lakhs from commercial = ‚Çπ22 Lakhs total</p>
                <p style="color: var(--color-danger); font-weight: bold;">‚ûú You MUST register for GST</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <h2><span class="emoji">‚ö†Ô∏è</span> What Happens At ‚Çπ20 Lakhs?</h2>
                <p>The moment you cross ‚Çπ20 Lakhs:</p>
                <div class="timeline">
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <div class="timeline-item-title">Registration Becomes Mandatory</div>
                        <p>You must register within 30 days</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <div class="timeline-item-title">You Become a "Registered Person"</div>
                        <p>This changes how tax is calculated</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <div class="timeline-item-title">New Tax Rules Apply</div>
                        <p>Different for each property</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <div class="timeline-item-title">File Monthly Returns</div>
                        <p>New compliance obligations</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card" style="margin-bottom: 25px;">
            <h2><span class="emoji">üèòÔ∏è</span> What Happens to Your RESIDENTIAL Property?</h2>
            
            <h3>Current Situation (Before ‚Çπ20 Lakhs):</h3>
            <div class="scenario">
                <div class="scenario-content">
                    <p>‚úì <strong>NO GST</strong> is charged (it's exempt)</p>
                    <p>‚úì The company rents from you and <strong>handles all GST</strong> on their end (Reverse Charge Mechanism - RCM)</p>
                    <p>‚úì You receive full rent without collecting any tax</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px; background: #E8F5E9; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;"><strong>Example:</strong> If monthly rent is ‚Çπ1,00,000, you receive exactly ‚Çπ1,00,000. No GST.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <h3>After Registration (Above ‚Çπ20 Lakhs):</h3>
            
            <div style="background: #E3F2FD; border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0;">
                <h3 style="color: var(--color-secondary); margin-top: 0;">Company Continues Under RCM (Reverse Charge)</h3>
                <div class="scenario" style="margin-top: 12px;">
                    <div class="scenario-content">
                        <p><strong>‚úÖ How it works (RECOMMENDED):</strong></p>
                        <ul style="margin-left: 20px; line-height: 1.8;">
                            <li>Company continues to pay GST themselves (RCM)</li>
                            <li>You don't collect or pay any GST</li>
                            <li>You receive full rent amount - NO CHANGE</li>
                            <li>Company issues self-invoice for GST</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p style="margin-top: 12px; background: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;"><strong>‚úÖ This is SIMPLER - No extra work for you. Everything stays the same.</strong></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="highlight">
                <p style="margin: 0;"><strong>‚úÖ BEST OPTION FOR YOU:</strong> Residential property to company continues under RCM. No change needed. Company handles GST as before.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card" style="margin-bottom: 25px;">
            <h2><span class="emoji">üè¢</span> What Happens to Your COMMERCIAL Property?</h2>
            
            <h3>Current Situation (Before ‚Çπ20 Lakhs):</h3>
            <div class="scenario">
                <div class="scenario-content">
                    <p>‚úì <strong>18% GST</strong> applies (it's not exempt)</p>
                    <p>‚úì The tenant pays GST under RCM</p>
                    <p>‚úì You don't collect GST yourself</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px; background: #E8F5E9; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;"><strong>Example:</strong> If rent is ‚Çπ40,000, tenant pays ‚Çπ40,000 to you + ‚Çπ7,200 GST to government</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <h3>After Registration (Above ‚Çπ20 Lakhs) - IMPORTANT CHANGE:</h3>
            <div class="scenario">
                <div class="scenario-content">
                    <p><strong>‚ö†Ô∏è THIS CHANGES - Latest Amendment October 10, 2024:</strong></p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 12px; background: #FFCDD2; padding: 12px; border-radius: 5px; font-weight: bold;">YOU MUST collect and pay GST (Forward Charge - FCM)</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 12px; font-size: 0.95em; background: #FFF9C4; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;"><strong>üìã Notification No. 09/2024:</strong> Once you're registered, you must use FCM for commercial property rentals. RCM no longer applies to registered landlords.</p>
                    
                    <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>What You Do:</strong></p>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 8px; line-height: 2;">
                        <li>Raise GST invoice showing 18% tax</li>
                        <li>Collect rent + GST from tenant</li>
                        <li>Pay GST to government monthly</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>The Numbers:</strong></p>
                    <div style="background: white; padding: 12px; border-radius: 5px; margin-top: 8px;">
                        <p>If monthly commercial rent is ‚Çπ40,000:</p>
                        <p style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 5px;">Base Rent: ‚Çπ40,000</p>
                        <p style="margin-left: 20px; color: var(--color-danger); font-weight: bold;">18% GST: ‚Çπ7,200</p>
                        <p style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 5px; border-top: 2px solid #ddd; padding-top: 8px; font-weight: bold;">Total: ‚Çπ47,200</p>
                        <p style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 8px; background: #FFEBEE; padding: 8px; border-radius: 5px; font-weight: bold;">You pay ‚Çπ7,200 GST to government</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card" style="margin-bottom: 25px; border-top-color: var(--color-warning);">
            <h2><span class="emoji">üìù</span> Latest GST Amendments (October 2024 - January 2025)</h2>
            <div style="background: #FFF3E0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px; margin: 15px 0;">
                <p><strong>üìã Notification No. 09/2024 - October 10, 2024:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin-left: 20px; line-height: 1.8; margin-top: 10px;">
                    <li><strong>Registered landlords:</strong> MUST use FCM (Forward Charge) for commercial property</li>
                    <li><strong>Unregistered landlords:</strong> Can use RCM for commercial property to registered tenants</li>
                    <li><strong>Key point:</strong> Landlord's registration status determines the mechanism</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <div style="background: #FFF3E0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px; margin: 15px 0;">
                <p><strong>üîî Clarification - January 16, 2025:</strong></p>
                <ul style="margin-left: 20px; line-height: 1.8; margin-top: 10px;">
                    <li>Composition scheme dealers: Can still use RCM on commercial property</li>
                    <li>Normal registered persons: MUST use FCM (no choice)</li>
                    <li>Residential property: RCM continues regardless of landlord registration status</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <p style="font-size: 0.95em; color: var(--color-text); margin-top: 15px;"><strong>üíº Bottom Line:</strong> Once you register, commercial property taxes shift to FCM. Residential remains under RCM.</p>
        </div>
        
